// CATEGORY: Hair Treatment Products
promptHairtreatNoDamage claimText MEANS
  CONCAT
    "REGULATORY TEST: Unsubstantiated No-Damage Claims (Hair Treatment Category)\n",
    "Context: Thai Cosmetics Manual BE 2567, Category 10 (Hair Treatment), p.32\n\n",
    "Principle: Hair straightening/perming/coloring products must indicate effects are\n",
    "not permanent and advise patch tests. They cannot claim \"no damage\" unless they\n",
    "contain conditioning agents and this is supported by scientific data.\n\n",
    "Decision Boundary:\n",
    "✅ ACCEPTABLE (proper treatment claims):\n",
    "  - States effects are \"not permanent\"\n",
    "  - Includes \"patch test before use\" advisory\n",
    "  - \"does not damage hair\" ONLY IF:\n",
    "    * Contains hair conditioning agent that helps protect/nourish, AND\n",
    "    * Supported by relevant scientific data\n",
    "    * May convey: \"contains hair-nourishing ingredients\" or \"hair-nourishing formula\"\n\n",
    "❌ PROHIBITED (unsubstantiated no-damage claims):\n",
    "  - \"does not damage hair\" without conditioning agents\n",
    "  - \"does not damage hair\" without scientific data support\n",
    "  - Implies permanent effects\n",
    "  - No patch test advisory\n\n",
    "Key distinction: Substantiated no-damage (with conditioning agents + data) ✓ vs.\n",
    "unsubstantiated no-damage claims ✗\n\n",
    "Evaluate this claim: ", claimText, "\n\n",
    "Question: Does this claim assert the product \"DOES NOT DAMAGE HAIR\" without\n",
    "either conditioning agents OR scientific data support?\n\n",
    "Answer with:\n",
    "- YES (violates hair treatment rules - prohibited) or NO (acceptable)\n",
    "- UNKNOWN (cannot determine substantiation)\n",
    "- Confidence: [0-100]%\n",
    "- Reasoning: [1-2 sentences explaining your judgment]"

// CATEGORY: Deodorant Products
promptDeodorantGlandStructure claimText MEANS
  CONCAT
    "REGULATORY TEST: Sweat Gland Structure Claims (Deodorant Category)\n",
    "Context: Thai Cosmetics Manual BE 2567, Category 11 (Deodorant), p.33\n\n",
    "Principle: Deodorant cosmetics can claim to reduce body odor and control\n",
    "underarm odor by reducing moisture, thereby reducing unwanted odor. They cannot\n",
    "claim to reduce sweat production or affect sweat gland structure. Claims about\n",
    "duration must be supported by testing.\n\n",
    "Decision Boundary:\n",
    "✅ ACCEPTABLE (odor control via moisture reduction):\n",
    "  - \"reducing body odor and controlling underarm odor caused by sweat\"\n",
    "  - \"by reducing moisture in the underarm area, thereby reducing unwanted odor\"\n",
    "  - Must include: \"results may vary depending on individual conditions\"\n",
    "  - Duration claims (\"24 hours\") must be supported by efficacy testing\n",
    "  - Temporary effect while on skin\n",
    "  - May contain astringent substances or pore-closing ingredients\n\n",
    "❌ PROHIBITED (sweat production/gland structure):\n",
    "  - \"reduces sweat production\"\n",
    "  - \"affects the structure of sweat glands\"\n",
    "  - \"reduces the number of sweat glands\"\n",
    "  - \"affects the sweating process\"\n",
    "  - Suggests use on skin with medical conditions (e.g., ingrown hair)\n",
    "  - Any claim about altering gland structure or function\n\n",
    "Note: Cosmetics may temporarily close pores but must not alter sweat gland structure.\n\n",
    "Key distinction: Reduces odor via moisture reduction ✓ vs. reduces sweat production or alters gland structure ✗\n\n",
    "Evaluate this claim: ", claimText, "\n\n",
    "Question: Does this claim imply the product REDUCES SWEAT PRODUCTION or AFFECTS\n",
    "SWEAT GLAND STRUCTURE, rather than just controlling odor by reducing moisture?\n\n",
    "Answer with:\n",
    "- YES (violates deodorant rules - prohibited) or NO (acceptable)\n",
    "- Confidence: [0-100]%\n",
    "- Reasoning: [1-2 sentences explaining your judgment]"

